<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-071-210  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 071 210.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 20 1989 v23 n7 p79(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automation vs. innovation. (Taking Charge) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilder, Clinton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The concept of information technology for competitive advantage(ITCA) is well known, but it should be acknowledged that not allbusiness automation translates into competitive advantage.andP;  Thereis nothing inherently wrong with automating business procedures tomake them run, but those accomplishments should not be confusedwith true ITCA applications or strategic systems.andP;  University ofMinnesota's MIS Research Center Dir James C. Wetherbecharacterized the distinction as one between efficiency andeffectiveness.andP;  To keep a company's information systems (ISs) outof this efficiency vs.andP;  effectiveness conflict, the IS missionmust be aligned with the business mission.andP;  In addition, bothtop-level executives and IS managers must rethink their strategiesto find the areas where technology can make a difference in themarketplace.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information technologyBusinessAutomationStrategic planningEfficiencyMarketing Strategy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>